exchanges.description:
Coal exports to India are medium grade and low grade (RB2(5700) and RB3), with CV of 22-25 MJ/kg and ash content 17-23%. As such this market is supplied predominantly by lower grade washed coal products (particularly the middlings product) and to a lessor degree higher grade unwashed coal (estimated at 5% of the supply to Indial).  Product losses are assumed to arise only from particulate emissions. Due to a lack of site specific data, this value is based on emission factors for loading, unloading, transit and stockpiling stages. Up to 14% of coal arriving at the export terminal is loaded directly onto waiting ships, thus emissions associated with stockpiling 14% of the coal was exluded. Losses on the Indian side taken from the Indian CERC (Central Electricity regulatory Commision) guidelines which gives a loss of 0.8 % as transit and handling loss for non pit-head power plants.

Sources: 
Emission factors for loading, unloading and transit via rail and ship from Chadwick, M. J., Highton, N.H. and Lindman, N. (1987) Environmental Impacts of Coal Mining and Utilization: A Complete Revision of Environmental Implications of Expanded Coal Utilization;
Emissions factors for loading/unloading of stockpile and during stockpiling due to wind erosion from NPI (2012) Emission Estimation Technique Manual for Mining. Version 3.1, National Pollution Inventory, Available at: http://www.npi.gov.au/system/files/resources/7e04163a-12ba-6864-d19a-f57d960aae58/files/mining.pdf. (Accessed on: July 2017);
Percentage of coal loaded directly onto ships from RBCT (2014) Company Website: Infrastructure, Richards Bay Coal Terminal. Available at: https://www.rbct.co.za/operations-6/infrastructure/. (Accessed July 2017).
